{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nThe code-review gate cast ZERO 'BLOCK — finding' votes across 162 changes since the code-v2 impact model landed, while 76% of changes carried advisories and at least three carried confirmed must-fix findings (#529 impact 0.0 — proved out on main within the hour; #518 importlib code-execution at 0.54; #539 correctness at 0.60). Observed impact distribution clusters at {0, 0.32, 0.36, 0.54, 0.60} with an apparent 0.60 ceiling — the 0.95 default threshold is unreachable. Before enabling blocking we need the empirically-correct threshold, not a guess: the operator's decision rule is the crossover point at which a finding is MORE LIKELY correctly-blocking than false-blocking (0.6 is the prior/starting hypothesis).\n\n## What\n- Assemble the post-2026-07-08 code-v2 corpus: the ~149 deduplicated code-review finding records in the ticket store (.tickets-tracker). NOTE on schema: code-review sidecars use `schema: code_review_result_v1` and store findings under `blocking`/`advisory`/`coaching` buckets (each with an `impact`), keyed by `target_ticket`/`change_fingerprint` — NOT the plan-review `plan_review_result_v1` shape (`findings`/`material_fingerprint`). Join to their Gerrit changes and post-merge history (follow-up fix commits, red-main incidents).\n- Adjudicate each finding with impact >= 0.3 as block-worthy vs not (blind to its score where feasible), mirroring the b463 plan-review methodology (manual scoring of the would-block slice; Sonnet-scored simulation with held-out adjudication acceptable for scale).\n- Compute precision(block-worthy | impact >= t) across candidate thresholds t in {0.3, 0.4, 0.5, 0.54, 0.6}; select the SMALLEST t where precision > 0.5, tie-broken toward fewer false blocks. Explicitly analyze the 0.54 band (the #518 security findings) and whether the 0.60 ceiling means t=0.6 only ever catches max-impact findings.\n- DERIVATION TOOLING (corrected): `calibrate_plan_review_thresholds.py` reads the PLAN-review sidecar schema and CANNOT consume code-review sidecars — do NOT reuse it for this corpus. Instead commit a dedicated code-review derivation script under docs/experiments/ (e.g. `derive_code_review_threshold.py`) that loads the `code_review_result_v1` sidecars (blocking/advisory buckets), joins the adjudication labels, and computes precision(block-worthy | impact >= t) across the candidate thresholds. Run `docs/experiments/ab_impact_model.py` (which IS the code-review-specific ADR-0036 A/B gate over the HIGH/NIT fixture) as the mandated evidence gate before any threshold-down. If extending the existing calibrator is preferred over a new script, its loader must first be taught the code-review schema and that change documented — but the default is the standalone code-review script.\n\n## Scope\nAnalysis + a written threshold recommendation recorded on this ticket (with the adjudication table as an artifact under docs/experiments/); NO routing/config change here (that is the sibling enablement story).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The adjudicated corpus (finding id, impact, adjudication, evidence) is committed under docs/experiments/ with the derivation script or notebook.\n- [ ] The chosen threshold and its precision-crossover justification are recorded in a comment on this ticket, including the 0.54-band and 0.60-ceiling analyses.\n- [ ] The ADR-0036 A/B gate result (HIGH<->NIT separation vs baseline) is recorded and passes.\n- [ ] make lint passes on the committed artifacts.\n- [ ] make test passes on the committed artifacts."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783888998638286001,"uuid":"82b85b1c-1ccb-414a-bd26-988e882bcdbb"}